          "text": "üìö Introduction"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "text": "Multiple Intelligence Theory, developed by Howard Gardner in 1983, suggests that intelligence is not a single entity, but rather a combination of different types of cognitive abilities. This revolutionary theory changed how we think about learning and education."
        },
        {
          "type": "divider"
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
          "level": 2,
          "text": "üß† The Eight Types of Intelligence"
        },
        {
          "type": "list",
          "ordered": true,
          "items": [
            "Linguistic Intelligence - The ability to use language effectively",
            "Logical-Mathematical Intelligence - Reasoning and problem-solving skills",
            "Spatial Intelligence - Understanding visual and spatial information",
            "Musical Intelligence - Sensitivity to rhythm, pitch, and melody",
            "Bodily-Kinesthetic Intelligence - Control of body movements",
            "Interpersonal Intelligence - Understanding others' emotions",
            "Intrapersonal Intelligence - Self-awareness and reflection",
            "Naturalist Intelligence - Recognition of patterns in nature"
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "card",
          "title": "üí° Key Concept",
          "content": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "text": "Everyone has all eight intelligences, but we each have a unique combination. Some intelligences are stronger than others in different individuals."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "heading",
